in the Dark Nektulos Forest, as the Dark Elves began<br>
their intonations... Watching the dead rise from their<br>
graves... Sensing twinges of pain and anguish come from the undead as unwilling spirits were<br>
imprisoned into the skeletal shells. The vile undead<br>
formed ranks behind their new masters and they marched<br>
off towards the commonlands. I followed a safe<br>
distance enveloped and hidden by the Hand of Tunare. <br>
The Tier'Dal suddenly scampered off of the road<br>
and took positions opposite one another. T'was then I<br>
heard the sound of hooves...and laughter...and<br>
children. It was most likely a gypsy caravan on its<br>
way to the trade bazaar in the commons. I knew what<br>
was sure to happen next, and began to meditate and<br>
summoned the strength of the earth itself and called<br>
forth the Spirit of the Wolf to aid me. As I mentally<br>
steeled myself for battle I flashed back...back to THE day...<br>
<br>
It was the day my my world died...I was returning home<br>
from a hunting expedition with a backpack full of<br>
foodstuffs. I stopped in mid-stride and dropped to the ground in a crouch becoming one with the forest. I could<br>
sense the fear of my animal friends. As I crept closer<br>
to the small hut my family called home, my sense of<br>
dread became palpable. I was horrified by what I saw.<br>
In plain view was an undead monstrosity chewing on a<br>
peice of flesh. My stomach knotted as I realized that<br>
peice of flesh was what was left of my father. With a<br>
gutteral, feral growl I lept at the foul abomination,<br>
swinging my oaken staff with a vengance. My blows<br>
seemed to have no effect and the creature began to<br>
beat me...brutally beat me. In a haze of blood and<br>
pain I saw a thin, dark skinned elf grinning cruelly<br>
at me. His grin turned into a howl of pain as<br>
lightening struck his body, jolting him to the ground.<br>
The walking dead beast turned his attention from me<br>
and searched for this new threat. A short half man<br>
appeared seemingly from nowhere and began to strike at<br>
the beast with a curved blade. The creature was<br>
felled quickly, however the dark skinned elf was<br>
gone...vanished from sight. This half man came over<br>
to me as I lie bleeding on the ground and layed his<br>
hand upon me. I felt a benevolence enter me that was<br>
familiar and yet unknown at the same time. I lapsed<br>
into unconsciousness then...<br>
<br>
...Since that day I had hunted the Undead with like-minded individuals. However I had a growing suspicion<br>
that my energies, though not wasted, had been<br>
misplaced. This day I realized that tis not the<br>
undead that I should hunt, but instead their vile<br>
masters. Those who call them from the graves to do<br>
their bidding. So with the image of that cruel<br>
grinning Tier'Dal burned into my mind's eye, I sprang<br>
forth from my hiding place taking the foul Tier'dal by<br>
surprise. After a hard fought battle I stood over the<br>
dark skinned corpses, my hammer bloodied and my will<br>
drained. I knew that this was the beginning for me...<br>
<br>
...The bard at the table seemed to enjoy my tales of<br>
the past. Methinks he believed my story to be<br>
embellished by the wine but, alas, t'was all true. <br>
<br>
Greylok, the Silent Hunter<br>
Druid of 39 seasons<br>
Soldier of Tunare<br>
Defender of the Wall<br>
